{#n7}
It was usual for the pretended saints at that time to change their names from [p:Henry], [p:Edward], [p:Anthony], [p:William], which they regarded as heathenish, into others more sanctified and godly: Even the New Testament names, [p:James], Andrew, [p:John], [p:Peter], were not held in such regard as those which were borrowed from the Old Testament, [p:Hezekiah], Habbakuk, [p:Joshua], Zerobabel. Sometimes a whole godly sentence was adopted as a name. Here are the names of a jury said to be enclosed in the county of [l:Sussex] about that time.See Brome's Travels into [l:England], [p. 279.] "[p:Cromwell]," says Cleveland, "hath beat up his drums clean through the Old Testament. You may learn the genealogy of our Saviour by the names of his regiment. The muster-master has no other list, than the first chapter of [p:St. Matthew]." The brother of this Praise-god Barebone had for name, _If [p:Christ] had not died for you, you had been damned Barebone._ But the people, tired of this long name, retained only the last word, and commonly gave him the appellation of _Damn'd Barebone._

