{#n7}
[Carte's Ormond, vol. ii. p. 254.] This account seems better supported, than that in Ablancourt's Memoirs, that the chancellor chiefly pushed the Portuguese alliance. The secret transactions of the court of [l:England] could not be supposed to be much known to a French resident at [l:Lisbon]: And whatever opposition the chancellor might make, he would certainly endeavour to conceal it from the queen and all her family; and even in the parliament and council would support the resolution already taken. _Clarendon himself says in his Memoirs, that he never either opposed or promoted the Portuguese match._

{#n8}
